Interview Questions
1) What is Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)?
-->Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm that organizes software using objects and classes.
    It focuses on modeling real-world entities with data (fields/variables) and behavior (methods/functions).
    Example:
    Car → object
    Speed, color → data
    Start(), stop() → behavior


2) What are the main principles/features of OOP? Explain each briefly?
-->The four main principles of OOP are:
    1. Encapsulation
    
    Binding data and methods together into a single unit (class) and restricting direct access to data.
    
    Example:
    class Student {
        private int marks;
    
        public void setMarks(int marks) {
            this.marks = marks;
        }
    
        public int getMarks() {
            return marks;
        }
    }
    Advantage:
    Provides data security
    Prevents unauthorized access
    
    
    2. Inheritance
    
    One class acquires properties and behaviors of another class.
    
    Example:
    class Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
        }
    }
    
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void bark() {
            System.out.println("Dog barks");
        }
    }
    Advantage:
    Code reusability
    Reduces duplication
    
    
    3. Polymorphism
    
    One action can behave differently in different situations.
    
    Types:
    
    Method Overloading → Compile-time polymorphism
    Method Overriding → Runtime polymorphism
    Example:
    class A {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Class A");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Class B");
        }
    }
    
    
    4. Abstraction
    
    Hiding implementation details and showing only essential features.
    
    Example:
    abstract class Vehicle {
        abstract void start();
    }
    Advantage:
    Reduces complexity
    Improves maintainability
    



3) What is an Object in Java?
-->An object is an instance of a class that contains data (state) and behavior (methods). In Java, objects are created in heap memory.
    It is an instance of a class.
    
    Example:
    Car c1 = new Car();
    
    Here:
    
    Car → class
    c1 → object


4) What is a Class in Java? How is it different from an Object?
-->A class is a blueprint/template for creating objects.
                            (OR)
    "A class is a template or blueprint that defines the data and methods that its objects will have. It is the foundation of OOP 
    because it describes the structure and behavior of the objects created from it."
    A class is loaded into the Method Area, which is a logical part of the JVM memory that stores class-level information.
| Class               | Object           |
| ------------------- | ---------------- |
| Blueprint           | Instance         |
| Logical entity      | Physical entity  |
| No memory allocated | Memory allocated |
| Declared once       | Can create many  |


5) What is the difference between Procedural (functional) Programming and Object-Oriented Programming?
-->
| Procedural Programming                   | OOP                       |
| ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Based on functions                       | Based on objects          |
| Data and functions separate              | Data and methods together |
| Less security                            | More security             |
| Difficult to maintain large applications | Easier maintenance        |
| Example: C                               | Example: Java             |


6) Why is OOP better for real-world applications?
-->OOP is better because:
    
    Models real-world entities naturally
    Provides code reusability
    Easier maintenance
    Better security using encapsulation
    Easy debugging and testing
    Supports modular programming
    Example:
    Banking systems, e-commerce apps, hospital management systems.



7) Why is Java considered a pure Object-Oriented language? Is it fully true?
-->Java is called mostly object-oriented because:
    
    Everything is organized into classes and objects.
    Supports major OOP principles.
    
    But Java is not fully pure OOP because:
    
    Primitive data types exist (int, char, boolean, etc.)
    Static methods and variables exist
    
    So Java is:      
    Not 100% pure object-oriented language



8) How does OOP support security in applications
-->OOP provides security mainly through:  
    Encapsulation:
    Access modifiers (private, protected, public)
    Example:
    private int salary;
    
    Direct access is restricted, so data is protected.
    
    Benefits:
    Prevents unauthorized access
    Data hiding
    Controlled modification using getters/setter



9) What happens in memory when an object is created?
-->Example:
    
    Student s = new Student();
    Memory Allocation:
    new Student() creates object in Heap Memory
    Reference variable s stored in Stack Memory
    Constructor initializes object
    Diagram:
    Stack Memory          Heap Memory
    -------------         ----------------
    s  ----------->       Student Object



10) Can a class exist without objects? Explain with example?
-->Yes, a class can exist without creating objects.    
    Example:
    class Test {
        static void display() {
            System.out.println("Hello");
        }
    }
    We can call:
    Test.display();
    
    without creating object:
    // No object created
    Because static members belong to the class.


11) What is an immutable object? How to create one in Java?
-->An immutable object is an object whose state cannot be changed after creation.
    
    Example:
    Java String class.
    
    Steps to create immutable class:
    Declare class as final
    Make fields private final
    No setters
    Initialize values using constructor
    Provide only getters
    Example:
    final class Employee {
    
        private final int id;
    
        Employee(int id) {
            this.id = id;
        }
    
        public int getId() {
            return id;
        }
    }



